05760nam a22008295i 9780231551014DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019023881  a97802315510147 a10.7312/quin164362doi  a(DE-B1597)541720  a(OCoLC)1135443450  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1995.9.N4bQ54 2019 4aPN1995.9.N4bQ54 2020 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43 6529960732231 aQuinn, Eithne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Piece of the Action :bRace and Labor in Post–Civil Rights Hollywood /cEithne Quinn. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b18 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. “The Screen Speaks for Itself ”: Institutional Discrimination and the Dawning of Hollywood Postracialism -- t2. Racializing the Hollywood Renaissance: Black and White Symbol Creators in a Time of Crisis -- t3. Challenging Jim Crow Crews: Federal Activism and Industry Reaction -- t4. “Getting the Man’s Foot out of Our Collective Asses”: Black Left Film Producers and the Rise of the Hustler Creative -- t5. Color- Blind Corporatism: The Black Film Wave and White Revival -- tConclusion: Race, Creative Labor, and Reflexivity in Post– Civil Rights Hollywood -- tNotes -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHollywood is often thought of—and certainly by Hollywood itself—as a progressive haven. However, in the decade after the passage of the Civil Rights Act, the film industry grew deeply conservative when it came to conflicts over racial justice. Amid black self-assertion and white backlash, many of the most heated struggles in film were fought over employment. In A Piece of the Action, Eithne Quinn reveals how Hollywood catalyzed wider racial politics, through representation on screen as well as in battles over jobs and resources behind the scenes.Based on extensive archival research and detailed discussions of films like In the Heat of the Night, Sweet Sweetback’s Baadasssss Song, Super Fly, Claudine, and Blue Collar, this volume considers how issues of race and labor played out on the screen during the tumultuous early years of affirmative action. Quinn charts how black actors leveraged their performance capital to force meaningful changes to employment and film content. She examines the emergence of Sidney Poitier and other African Americans as A-list stars; the careers of black filmmakers such as Melvin Van Peebles and Ossie Davis; and attempts by the federal government and black advocacy groups to integrate cinema. Quinn also highlights the limits of Hollywood’s liberalism, showing how predominantly white filmmakers, executives, and unions hid the persistence of racism behind feel-good stories and public-relations avowals of tolerance. A rigorous analysis of the deeply rooted patterns of racial exclusion in American cinema, A Piece of the Action sheds light on why conservative and corporate responses to antiracist and labor activism remain pervasive in today’s Hollywood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAfrican Americans in motion pictures. 0aAfrican Americans in the motion picture industry. 0aHistory. 0aMotion picturesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictures. 0aRace in motion pictures. 0aRace relations in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 